response_text:
**Vulnerability Class:** Stack-based Buffer Overflow (CWE-121)

**Location:** `prompt.c`, line 7

**Explanation:** 
The function `gets()` does not perform any bounds checking on the input it reads. It will continue reading characters from `stdin` until it encounters a newline or EOF, regardless of the size of the destination buffer (`name[64]`). An attacker can provide an input longer than 63 characters (plus the null terminator) to overwrite the stack, which can lead to a crash or the execution of arbitrary code by overwriting the function's return address.

**Proposed Fix:** 
Replace `gets()` with `fgets()`, which allows you to specify the maximum number of characters to read.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void prompt_name(void) {
    char name[64];
    printf("Enter your name: ");
    // Read up to 63 characters to leave room for the null terminator
    if (fgets(name, sizeof(name), stdin) != NULL) {
        printf("Hello, %s!\n", name);
    }
}
```

