### 2. Buffer Over-read (CWE-125)
**Location:** `buffer.cpp` line 21 (`std::puts(dst.raw());`)

**Explanation:** 
The `std::memcpy` call on line 20 copies exactly 5 bytes ("hello") into the buffer. It does not append a null terminator (`\0`). The `std::puts` function expects a null-terminated C-string and will continue reading memory past the 5 bytes of "hello" until it encounters a null byte in memory. This results in an out-of-bounds read, which can leak sensitive information from the heap.

**Proposed Fix:** 
Ensure the buffer is null-terminated before passing it to `std::puts`.

```cpp
void copy_and_log(Buffer src) {
    Buffer dst = src;
    const char* msg = "hello";
    size_t len = 5;
    if (dst.size() > len) {
        std::memcpy(dst.raw(), msg, len);
        dst.raw()[len] = '\0'; // Manually null-terminate
        std::puts(dst.raw());
    }
}
```

